Gavin's Personas Dad & Sister
Joe - Senior Sales (Dad)

Joe, age 49. He works as a salesman for Lamar Advertising, and he sells billboard space across the markets Madison - Rockford. 
He earns approximately $200,000 per year through salary and commission and has worked in this job for over 8 years. 
His company offers a strong 401(k) match, and Joe consistently contributes to his retirement plan, so he is not particularly worried about long-term financial security. 
He is married to a school principal, and together they maintain a comfortable dual-income household with four children that are all in college or moved out. 
He still supports all the children with needed expenses.

Joe pays for all four children’s car insurance policies, maintains an $800 monthly car payment, and recently purchased a $35,000 collection car. 
He has also made impulsive purchases such as boats and additional vehicles in the past. 
He covers the phone bill for six people and generally makes most financial decisions himself, although overall household finances are relaxed and stable. 
While he does not feel stressed about money, he has recently become frustrated with how many expenses are spread across different accounts and where they come from. 
After noticing several recurring subscription charges on his card, he ended up pausing a credit card to simplify things and restart. 
Joe is very comfortable with technology and uses digital tools daily for work. If he were to use a financial tracking system, he would want something simple and automated that gives him a clear overview of where his money is going without requiring detailed budgeting. 
He wants a good display of where his money is going into categories and be able to store it on his computer in a CSV file to replace his current budgeting process.

Paige - Project Manager at Hendericks Building (Sister)

Paige, age 27. She works in a corporate role earning between $70,000 and $80,000 per year. 
She and her fiance, who earns about $100,000 annually by herself. 
Recently purchased a starter home and are currently planning a wedding that will cost around $35,000. 
They are sharing wedding expenses and receiving some help from family. 
Although their combined income provides stability, Paige feels some financial stress due to the high cost of the wedding and the responsibility of managing a mortgage at the same time.

Paige and her fiance make financial decisions together rather than having one person take full control. 
In the short term, her goal is to complete the wedding without unnecessary debt. 
In the long term, she hopes to move into a larger home, purchase a new car, and eventually start a family. 
She recently has paid off her school debt goal. Because of these goals, understanding where their money goes each month is very important to her future. 
She does not currently use a budgeting app but is highly comfortable with technology, as is her fiance. 
A financial management system that allows shared access, tracks spending categories clearly, and shows progress toward savings goals would help reduce her stress and support their future plans.


